break:

section: 01. Executive Summary

sub: The Opportunity
text: Qatar consumes roughly QAR 18.8 million of raw printing inks every year (2024, GASTAT) and manufactures *none* of it — every litre is imported, on lead times of 6–14 weeks. Medad Ink Factory establishes the State's first ink-manufacturing plant in the Manateq Industrial Zone, producing commercial printing inks, writing and stationery inks, and specialty/industrial inks for the domestic market and, from Year 2, for export across the GCC.

sub: Why Now
- First mover — no ink manufacturer exists in Qatar; 100% import-substitution opportunity.
- Qatar-origin goods enter the GCC tariff-free under the customs union (export upside).
- Aligned with Qatar National Vision 2030's local-manufacturing priority; preliminary approval already issued.
- NFE LNG expansion is driving construction, packaging, media and signage — all ink-intensive.

sub: The Ask
text: QAR 3.80 million of equity to build a 500-tonne/year plant returning an IRR of ~38% with payback inside three years.

sub: The Numbers
metric: Investment | value: 3.80M | unit: QAR
metric: NPV @ 10% | value: 4.1M | unit: QAR | trend: up | period: 5 years
metric: IRR | value: 38% | target: 10% hurdle
metric: Payback | value: 2.7 yrs
metric: Y5 EBITDA margin | value: 38%

info: A compact, capital-light project with strong, debt-free returns. | type: success

break:

section: 02. Market

sub: Market Size
text: Qatar's raw printing-ink imports (HS 3215) reached QAR 18.8 million in 2024, having grown at a 5.6% compound annual rate since 2020. The market is supplied entirely by imports — there is no domestic manufacturer. Separately, printer cartridges (HS 8443) represent a much larger QAR 118 million market that Medad may address in a future phase but which is excluded from this study's base case.

metric: TAM 2024 | value: 18.8M | unit: QAR
metric: CAGR 2020–24 | value: 5.6% | trend: up
metric: Local supply | value: Zero
metric: GCC export market | value: 185M | unit: USD

sub: Competitive Landscape
text: No local manufacturer; competition is entirely imported brands and distributors.

| Force | Assessment |
| Local manufacturers | None — Medad would be the first and only one in Qatar. |
| Imported brands | Huber, Toyo, Sun Chemical, BASF, Siegwerk — strong but remote. |
| Distributors | Regional (mostly UAE) resellers; carry inventory and FX cost. |
| Buyer power | Moderate — printers are loyal but frustrated by lead times/MOQs. |
| New entrants | A UAE manufacturer could follow; first-mover and origin lock-in matter. |
| Substitutes | None for ink itself; price competition from Chinese grades on commodities. |

info: The gap — there is no GCC-based ink manufacturer serving Qatar. Medad fills a clear structural gap rather than fighting an entrenched local incumbent. | type: tip

sub: GCC Export Market
text: A USD 185M regional market reachable tariff-free from Qatar.

| Market | Annual ink imports | Notes |
| Saudi Arabia | USD 70M | Largest GCC printing industry |
| UAE | USD 52M | Dubai regional printing hub |
| Kuwait | USD 22M | Growing commercial print sector |
| Oman | USD 18M | Industrial labelling demand |
| Bahrain + Qatar | USD 23M | Smaller but adjacent |

info: Domestic demand alone cannot fill a 500-tonne plant. Tariff-free GCC export (under the customs union) lifts utilisation toward 90%+ and is the key driver of the project's higher-capacity-year returns. | type: info

break:

section: 03. Technical

sub: Facility Overview
text: A 1,200 sqm leased plant in Manateq configured for liquid-ink manufacturing.

| Parameter | Specification |
| Product | Printing, writing and specialty liquid inks |
| Technology | Dispersing, mixing, bead/roll milling, let-down, filling |
| Facility area | 1,200 sqm |
| Location | Manateq Industrial Zone, Qatar |
| Lease term | 10 years |
| Installed capacity | 500 tonnes/year |

info: Why Manateq — purpose-built industrial zone with utilities, road access and low-cost land (~QAR 10/sqm/year), plus streamlined civil-defence and environmental permitting for chemical light-manufacturing. | type: info

sub: Production Process
text: A 12-step batch process from raw-material receipt to QC-released dispatch.

1. Raw-material receipt & inspection (COA, viscosity, colour index)
2. Batch formulation planning (formula card, batch size)
3. Pre-dispersion — pigment into resin vehicle (high-speed disperser)
4. Bead / triple-roll milling — particle size < 5 microns
5. Viscosity adjustment & additive let-down
6. Colour measurement (ΔE < 2 vs. target)
7. Tack, gloss & rub-resistance testing
8. pH & stability testing (water-based)
9. QC approval — transfer to filling
10. Filling (5L, 10L, 25L, 200L containers)
11. Labelling (lot number, MSDS, expiry)
12. Final QC check & dispatch documentation

info: Batch traceability — every batch carries a lot number linked to its raw-material lots, enabling full traceability and consistent colour, the critical quality parameter for printers. | type: tip

sub: Capacity & Output Ramp
text: 500 t/year installed; output ramps with market penetration and export.

| Metric | Y1 | Y2 | Y3 | Y4 | Y5 |
| Utilisation | 38% | 48% | 65% | 82% | 88% |
| Output (tonnes) | 188 | 238 | 324 | 410 | 439 |
| Revenue (QAR '000) | 3,675 | 4,650 | 6,475 | 8,400 | 9,000 |

